Hi there,=20

 Today, Intel released a statement regarding two Processors Data Leakage <h=
ttps://blogs.intel.com/technology/2020/01/ipas-intel-sa-00329/> security vu=
lnerabilities (Vector Register Sampling and L1D Eviction Sampling), that ma=
y allow unintended information disclosure for users of multi-tenant cloud e=
nvironments. On DigitalOcean=E2=80=99s platform, these two vulnerabilities =
may allow malicious actors to theoretically use a Droplet to infer partial =
data used by previously run software or by another Droplet on the same phys=
ical host.=20

 These vulnerabilities are similar to L1 Terminal Fault (L1TF) <https://blo=
g.digitalocean.com/a-message-about-l1tf/> as well as the Microarchitectural=
 Data Sampling (MDS) <https://blog.digitalocean.com/may-2019-intel-vulnerab=
ility/> and Transactional Asynchronous Abort (TAA)=20
processor-level issues we=E2=80=99ve mitigated previously. However, the Vec=
tor Register Sampling vulnerability has a smaller scope and lower risk than=
 MDS, and the L1TF mitigations DigitalOcean applied previously will help pr=
event a malicious Droplet from attacking a host with L1D Eviction Sampling.=
=20

 To further mitigate the impact of these two vulnerabilities, we are workin=
g with Intel to obtain updated microcode, which we hope to receive soon. On=
ce received, our engineering team will begin to rapidly and thoroughly test=
, and then roll out the updated microcode across our fleet.=20

 Updates from Intel and our own mitigation efforts will be ongoing. As new =
information becomes available, we=E2=80=99ll share updates here <https://bl=
og.digitalocean.com/an-update-about-intels-recent-cve-announcement/>. We=E2=
=80=99ll also follow up with another email message once we=E2=80=99ve final=
ized mitigations and our platform is protected.

 Thanks,=20
Team DigitalOcean
